
🛡️ 'Stay Safe Online' Checklist
[ ] Enable Two-Factor Authentication (2FA): Activate 2FA on your college email, LinkedIn, and social media accounts. Use an authenticator app rather than just SMS to prevent SIM-swapping attacks.
[ ] Secure Your UPI PIN: Never enter your UPI PIN to receive money. Remember: A PIN is only required to send money or check your balance, never for incoming payments.
[ ] Verify "Requests" on Payment Apps: Be cautious of "Collect Requests" on apps like PhonePe or Google Pay from unknown numbers claiming you’ve won a prize or a scholarship.
[ ] Use Strong, Unique Passwords: Avoid using your name, date of birth, or "123456." Use a mix of uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols. Never reuse the same password for your bank and your social media.
[ ] Beware of Public Wi-Fi: Avoid logging into bank accounts or student portals while connected to free campus or cafe Wi-Fi. If necessary, use a trusted VPN to encrypt your data.
[ ] Think Before You Click: Scrutinize links in "Urgent" emails or WhatsApp messages claiming your SIM card will be blocked or your KYC needs immediate updating.
[ ] Check App Permissions: Regularly audit the apps on your phone. Revoke access to your camera, microphone, or contacts for apps that don't strictly need them to function.
[ ] Keep Software Updated: Always install the latest security patches for your Android/iOS and your browser. These updates often fix "zero-day" vulnerabilities used by hackers.
🚨 How to Report Cybercrime
If you or someone you know falls victim to a scam, immediate reporting is crucial for the chance of fund reversal or legal action:
Online Portal: National Cyber Crime Reporting Portal
National Helpline: Call 1930 (Available 24/7)

